DURBAN - The eThekwini Municipality has taken drastic measures to curb the spread of coronavirus. Swimming at all beaches has been banned with immediate effect in response to President Cyril Ramaphosa's restrictions on gatherings of more than 100 people. READ: Saftu calls for compliance, better govt response to COVID-19 Some people who were interviewed by eNCA on the beaches of Durban said they were not aware of the regulations being implemented but once they learned of them, were willing to comply. Durbanites said they were "kinda bummed out" by the swimming ban but were understanding of the situation as it related to curbing the spread of COVID-19. WATCH: Small businesses to receive COVID-19 fund relief Visitors to the beaches are only allowed to walk along the promenade where there is visible policing and lifeguards are on call to disperse gatherings. oronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.